ics of repair invests in the horizon of difference that repetition materializes, and it extends reparations discourses intent on overcoming the past and calculating economic compensation for survivors of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGay peoplexViolence againstzJamaica. 0aHomophobiazJamaica. 0aHomosexualityzJamaicaxHistoriography. 0aHuman rightszJamaica. 0aSexual minoritieszJamaicaxHistoriography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Caribbean & Latin American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059233?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059233/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles